{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492777"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1154"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1154"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.04,0.17,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2164"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of night sweats and sore throat. He has recently returned from the Gold Coast. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies weight loss, fever, loss of appetite, cough, dyspnoea, or abdominal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is painful bilateral posterior cervical lymphadenopathy and exudate covering his left tonsil. His chest is clear on auscultation. There is fullness in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen. A heterophile antibody test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Symptomatic management","Oseltamivir","Phenoxymethylpenicillin","Prednisolone","Ganciclovir"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of infectious mononucleosis caused by \u003Cem\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/em\u003E: fever, exudative pharyngitis, and posterior cervical lymphadenopathy. Patients with clinical features suggestive of IM need to undergo a Monospot test that detects heterophile antibodies in the patient\u0027s serum. The patient\u0027s serum is mixed with sheep or horse RBCs. The heterophile antibodies react with the horse or sheep RBCs, leading to agglutination which confirms the diagnosis. The presence of splenomegaly (fullness in left upper quadrant) is also characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymptomatic management\u003C/strong\u003E with rest, adequate hydration, and analgesics/antipyretics is the mainstay of treatment. Patients should be advised to avoid contact sports for 3-4 weeks due to the risk of splenic rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOseltamivir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used for influenza within 48 hours of symptom onset. It would not be effective for infectious mononucleosis and the presentation is not consistent with influenza.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenoxymethylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for bacterial pharyngitis, particularly Group A Streptococcus, but the clinical features here are more consistent with viral infection. Additionally, patients with infectious mononucleosis who receive penicillins can develop a characteristic rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is only indicated in infectious mononucleosis if there are severe complications such as significant airway compromise, severe thrombocytopenia, or haemolytic anaemia. This patient has no such complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGanciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral used primarily for cytomegalovirus infections in immunocompromised patients. It has no role in the management of uncomplicated infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with infectious mononucleosis need only symptomatic management and advice to avoid contact sports.","The classic triad of infectious mononucleosis is fever, exudative pharyngitis, and posterior cervical lymphadenopathy.","Corticosteroids are only indicated in infectious mononucleosis if there is airway compromise or severe complications."],"references":["Sylvester JE, Buchanan BK, Silva TW. Infectious Mononucleosis: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2023;107(1):71-78.","Mohseni M, Boniface MP, Graham C. Mononucleosis. [Updated 2020 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470387/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1154"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:03:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:04:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1154"}},"content":{"data":